<subSubSection id="C36165495E3EFF9E9EBDFF70FD559B6C" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3EFF9E9EBDFF70FD439A4C" blockId="7.[174,1232,239,842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">
Diagnosis. Green lacewings (
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9C04FF70FD05992C" authorityName="Schneider" authorityYear="1851" box="[602,759,239,266]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysopidae</taxonomicName>
) are one of the largest families among 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9EF0FE90FECE990C" box="[174,316,271,298]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Neuroptera</taxonomicName>
. There are about 1,300 currently recognized species in the world, included in 87 genera and 3 subfamilies. The adults are mostly predators, but a few species feed on pollen. The adults have symmetrical mandibles and long setaceous antennae, which may exceed the length of the wing two times. The wings are large (hind wings slightly smaller than fore wings), semi-transparent, iridescent; veins mainly greenish or brownish. In contrast to other neuropterans, the chrysopids’ wing membrane is without microtrichia and 
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3EFF9E9EBCFE4FFEF899CF" box="[226,266,464,489]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">trz.</emphasis>
The pterostigma is not always visible. Wing veins are covered with setae on both sides, forming a dense fringe in some members of the family. The jugulum lobe of the wing is present only in the most primitive species of the family. Wings have a characteristic venation, which is of great value for identifying the taxa (
<figureCitation id="13402A475E3EFF9E9D05FDB0FC659A6C" box="[859,919,559,586]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1767,1789]" captionTargetBox="[188,1160,1062,1743]" captionTargetId="figure-454@1.[170,1228,1045,1744]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. General scheme for wing venation in Chrysopidae (legend on the FIgure): Psm — pseudomedian vein, Psc — pseudocubitus, ini — intramedian cell, G1 — gradiformes internal, GE — gradiformes exstemal, cv — cross veins of costal sector, pt — pterostigma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404182" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404182/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">FIg. 1</figureCitation>
) (e. g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9DACFDB0FF189A4C" author="Aspock, U. &amp; Aspock, H." pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="451 - 516" refId="ref6287" refString="Aspock, U. and Aspock, H. 2007. ' Verbliebene Vielfalt vergangener Blute. Zur Evolution. Phylogenie und Biodiversitat der Neuropterida (Insecta: Endopterygota). Denisia, 20, 451 - 516. URL: http: // www. zobodat. at / pdf / DENISIA _ 0020 _ 0451 - 0516. pdf." type="journal article" year="2007">Aspöck &amp; Aspöck, 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9EABFDD0FE3C9A4C" author="Zakharenko, A. V." box="[245,462,591,618]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="44 - 58" refId="ref6969" refString="Zakharenko, A. V. 1993. The green lace-wings (Neuroptera. Chrysopidae) of Ukraine. The Kharkov Entomological Society Gazette. 1 (1), 44 - 58. URL: http: // nbuv. gov. ua / UJRN / Vkhet _ 1993 _ 1 _ 1 _ 7 [In Russian]." type="journal article" year="1993">Zakharenko, 1993</bibRefCitation>
and many others).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC436C25E3EFF9E9EBDFDF0FD559B6C" blockId="7.[174,1232,239,842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">
The family 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9F34FDF0FE0D9AAC" authorityName="Schneider" authorityYear="1851" box="[362,511,623,650]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysopidae</taxonomicName>
includes three subfamilies: Apochrysinae, 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9DA1FDF0FB659AAC" box="[1023,1175,623,650]" pageId="7" pageNumber="109" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chrysopinae">Chrysopinae</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9EF0FD10FE9C9A8C" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1910" box="[174,366,655,682]" pageId="7" pageNumber="109" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Nothochrysinae">Nothochrysinae</taxonomicName>
. The distribution ranges of most members of Apochrysinae are restricted to the Southern Hemisphere: seven species of two genera are known from Central and South America; two genera with three species occur in 
<collectingCountry id="F36C76525E3EFF9E9C88FD50FC9E9ACC" box="[726,876,719,746]" name="South Africa" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">South Africa</collectingCountry>
; FIve genera with 14 species live in the Australian Region. In the Northern Hemisphere, the subfamily is represented by a single species — 
<taxonomicName id="4C7B4D415E3EFF9E9F28FC8FFCC79B0C" authority="Okamoto, 1912" authorityName="Okamoto" authorityYear="1912" box="[374,821,783,810]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Nacaura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matsumurae">
<emphasis id="B90FEAD05E3EFF9E9F28FC8FFD8A9B0F" box="[374,632,784,809]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">Nacaura matsumurae</emphasis>
Okamoto, 1912
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F36C76525E3EFF9E9DDEFC90FC319B0C" box="[896,963,783,810]" name="Japan" pageId="7" pageNumber="108">Japan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9D8CFC90FB839B0C" author="Brooks, S. J." box="[978,1137,783,810]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="267 - 275" refId="ref6349" refString="Brooks, S. J. 1997 An overview of the current status of Chrysopidae (Neuroptera) systematics. Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift. 44 (2), 267 - 275." type="journal article" year="1997">Brooks, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9A22FC90FF1B9B6C" author="Holzel, H." pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="61 - 68" refId="ref6442" refString="Holzel, H. 1984. Chrysopidae of the Palearctic Region - a review'. In: Gepps, J., Aspock, H. and Holzel, H., eds. Progress in World's Neuropterology. Graz, 61 - 68. URL: http: // www. zobodat. at / pdf / MONO-ENT- NEURO _ MEN 1 _ 0061 - 0068. pdf." type="book chapter" year="1984">Hölzel, 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9EADFCB0FE799B6C" author="Toschi, C. A." box="[243,395,815,842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="391 - 433" refId="ref6890" refString="Toschi, C. A. 1965. The taxonomy life histories and mating behavior of the green lacewings of Strawberry Canyon (Neuroptera, Chrysopidae). Hilgardia, 36, 391 - 433." type="journal article" year="1965">Toschi, 1965</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFEA4B335E3EFF9E9FC8FCB0FD699B6C" author="Winterton, S. L. &amp; Brooks, S. J." box="[406,667,815,842]" pageId="7" pageNumber="108" pagination="71 - 81" refId="ref6926" refString="Winterton, S. L., Brooks, S. J. 2015. Review of the green lacewing genus Chrysacanthia Lacroix with a new species from Nigeria (Neuroptera. Chrysopidae). ZooKeys, 517, 71 - 81." type="journal article" year="2015">Winterton et al., 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
